Adult.description: The easiest way to separate American Crows and Fish Crows is by their calls. American Crows give a burry, full-throated “caw”, while Fish Crows are more nasal sounding, often giving short “cow” notes in pairs. American Crows are slightly larger with broader wingtips, but visual identification is very difficult.
Common Ravens are much bigger and bulkier, with larger bills than Fish Crows.

Adult male.description: Boat-tailed Grackles are smaller and more slender, with much longer tails than Fish Crows.

Breeding adult.description: The European Starling is another widespread black bird that occurs in flocks, but it is far smaller than a Fish Crow with a longer, more slender bill.
